      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Why does a tiny change in distance produce a multiplicative change in current instead of a small, nearly linear response?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.19,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The naive model expects a gentle distance dependence. The real curve is exponential: current collapses by the same factor for every equal step away from the surface.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.18,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The vacuum gap is a barrier. An electron wave does not stop abruptly at the metal edge; its amplitude leaks into the gap and decays exponentially. Tunneling samples the tiny tail that reaches the other side.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "decay"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.16,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "The distance dependence is I proportional to e to the minus two kappa d.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.74,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Compare two gaps separated by delta d. Their current ratio is e to the minus two kappa delta d. With kappa near one per ångström, moving one ångström farther gives e to the minus two, about one over 7.4.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.59,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Reverse the move: one ångström closer changes delta d to minus one, so the ratio becomes e squared, about 7.4. Same formula, opposite direction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reverse"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.94,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Take the logarithm and the exponential becomes a straight line: log current equals a constant minus two kappa d. Its slope directly records the barrier decay constant.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.18,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:41:14"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Now put a one-ångström surface bump beneath the tip. At the same tip height, that local gap is one ångström smaller, so the bump produces roughly seven times the current of its flat neighbor.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "amplify"
